We need to assess if visualization described is misleading.

Description: line graph daily cases, y-axis 0-15,000, x axis dates. Vertical line at June 18. Shows low stable March-May, then increase late May/early June, accelerates after June 18, peaks late June/early July, slight decline mid-July. Also 7-day moving average line.

Caption claims mask mandate didn't curb spread, cases surged for six weeks after.

Potential issues: causal inference – attributing cause to mask mandate based on timing; correlation not causation. This is a "Causal inference" error. Also possibly cherry-picking: focusing only on this period, not longer term, not considering other factors. But the chart itself just shows data; the misleading part is in caption linking cause.

Also possibly "Truncated axis": Y-axis from 0 to 15,000 - starts at zero? It's said scaled from 0 to 15,000, so not truncated. So fine.

"Setting an arbitrary threshold": vertical line marking mask mandate is not a threshold but an event annotation. Not arbitrary threshold.

"Incorrect reading of chart": The author says increase becomes more pronounced after June 18, but may be that increase already underway; but that's basically interpretation; could be misreading that mask caused increase.

Thus main error: Causal inference (implying mask mandate ineffective). Also possibly cherry-picking (only showing short window). The visualization itself maybe not misleading but the caption is.

We need to decide if visualization is misleading: The chart itself might be fine, but the combination with caption is misleading because it infers causality. So overall the visualization (including caption) is misleading. So is_misleading = true.

Intentional? Likely intentional rhetorical framing to argue mask mandates ineffective. Could be intentional. Confidence moderate-high.
